    <title>Hadoop Ecosystem ++</title>
    <para>
        We met a few members of Hadoop eco system in <xref linkend="chapter-Intro"/>.  How ever hadoop eco system is much bigger than that, and it is growing at a rapid pace.  Keeping track of Hadoop components / products is now a full time job :-)
    </para>
    <para>
        In this chapter we are going to meet a few more members.  Some of them may not be Hadoop off shoots.  But they are often used along side Hadoop implementations.
    </para>

    <section>
        <title>Getting Data into HDFS</title>
        <para>
            Most of the big data originates outside Hadoop cluster.  These tools will help you get data into HDFS
        </para>

        <table id="table-hadoop-ecosystem-data-funnels">
            <title>Tools for Getting Data into HDFS</title>
            <tgroup cols='2' align='left' colsep='1' rowsep='1'>
                <thead>
                    <row>
                        <entry>Tool</entry>
                        <entry>Remarks</entry>
                    </row>
                </thead>
                <tbody>
                    <row>
                        <entry>
                            <link xlink:href="http://flume.apache.org/">Flume</link>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                            Gathers data from multiple sources and gets into HDFS
                        </entry>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <entry>
                            <link xlink:href="https://github.com/facebook/scribe">Scribe</link>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                            Distributed log gatherer.  Originally developed by Facebook.  Hasn't been updated recently.
                        </entry>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <entry>
                            <link xlink:href="http://incubator.apache.org/chukwa/">Chukwa</link>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                            Data collection system
                        </entry>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <entry>
                            <link xlink:href="http://sqoop.apache.org">Sqoop</link>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                            Transfer data between Hadoop and Relational Databases (RDBMS)
                        </entry>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <entry>
                            <link xlink:href="http://kafka.apache.org/">Kafka</link>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                            Distributed publish-subscribe system
                        </entry>
                    </row>
                </tbody>
            </tgroup>
        </table>


    </section>
    <section>
        <title>Querying data in HDFS</title>
        <table id="table-hadoop-ecosystem-querying">
            <title>Querying Data in HDFS</title>
            <tgroup cols='2' align='left' colsep='1' rowsep='1'>
                <thead>
                    <row>
                        <entry>Tool</entry>
                        <entry>Remarks</entry>
                    </row>
                </thead>
                <tbody>
                    <row>
                        <entry>
                            <link xlink:href="http://pig.apache.org/">Pig</link>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                            Pig provides a higher level data flow language to process data.  Pig scripts are much more compact than Java Map Reduce
                        </entry>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <entry>
                            <link xlink:href="http://hive.apache.org">Hive</link>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                            Hive provides a SQL layer on top of HDFS.  So we can query the data using SQL, rather than writing Java Map Reduce code.
                        </entry>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <entry>
                            <link xlink:href="http://www.cascading.org/lingual/">Cascading Lingual</link>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                            executes ANSI SQL queries as Cascading applications on Apache Hadoop clusters
                        </entry>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <entry>
                            <link xlink:href="http://hortonworks.com/blog/100x-faster-hive/">Stinger</link>  / <link xlink:href="http://hortonworks.com/blog/introducing-tez-faster-hadoop-processing/">Tez</link>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                            Next gen Hive
                        </entry>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <entry>
                            <link xlink:href="http://hadapt.com/">Hadapt</link>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                            Provides SQL support for Hadoop. <sbr/>
                            (commercial product)
                        </entry>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <entry>
                            <link xlink:href="http://www.greenplum.com/blog/topics/hadoop/introducing-pivotal-hd">Greenplum HAWQ</link>
                        </entry>
                        <entry>
                            Relational database with SQL support on top of Hadoop HDFS. <sbr/>
                            (Commercial product)
                        </entry>
                    </row>
                </tbody>
            </tgroup>
        </table>
    </section>


